      "tool": "websearch",
      "code": "{\"query\": \"WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR fix repair score iFixit repairability 2025 2026\", \"type\": \"fast\"}",
      "output": "Title: How Is the iFixit Repairability Score Calculated?\nURL: https://www.ifixit.com/News/75533/how-ifixit-scores-repairability\nPublished: 2026-07-01T17:29:20.000Z\nAuthor: Jeff Suovanen\nHighlights:\nOur baseline score considers three things: the service manual, availability of replacement parts, and the design of the product itself, aka design for ...\n\n---\n\nTitle: Repairability - iFixit\nURL: https://www.ifixit.com/repairability\nPublished: 2026-06-29T03:10:30.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nRepairability means making it possible—and ideally easy—to repair a product. A repairable product is designed with disassembly in mind.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR on Windows 11 | RebootDoctor\nURL: https://rebootdoctor.com/blog/whea-uncorrectable-error-windows-11/\nPublished: 2026-05-27T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nShort answer: WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR (0x00000124) is one of the few BSODs that genuinely means hardware — the CPU reported an error it could not self-correct. Check Event Viewer under WHEA-Logger for the source. Common culprits are unstable overclocks or XMP/EXPO memory profiles (disable them first), an overheating CPU, a failing PSU, or on Intel 13th/14th-gen chips the known voltage degradation.\n...\nIf you’re overclocking — CPU, RAM with XMP/EXPO, GPU — this is the crash that tells you to stop. An unstable overclock is the single most common trigger for WHEA errors on otherwise healthy hardware. The CPU is running at a voltage or frequency it can’t reliably sustain, and the error correction catches it.\n...\nDisable XMP in BIOS first. If the crashes stop, XMP was pushing the memory controller past what your particular CPU can handle. Try the default 2133 MHz (DDR4) or 4800 MHz (DDR5) for a week. If stable, re-enable XMP at a lower speed — step down one tier at a time until you find what’s stable.\n...\nIf you’ve overclocked the\n...\n, reset everything to stock. If you haven’t touched anything, check whether your\n...\n“auto overclock” feature is enabled — many boards ship with something\n...\n’s “AI Overclock Tuner” or MSI’s “Game Boost” turned on by default, pushing\n...\nIntel or AMD’s spec without telling you. Disable it.\n...\n“Bus/Interconnect Error\n...\nCould be a\n...\nbad connection, or a dying motherboard PCIe slot. Reseat\n...\nfirst — pull it\n...\npush it back\n...\n. Try a\n...\nInstall HWiNFO and check if thermal throttling or abnormal voltages precede the crashes. CPU hitting 100°C? The overheating is the real problem and WHEA is the symptom. VCore fluctuating wildly under load? PSU or VRM issue.\n...\nThis is the one BSOD where “run SFC and update drivers” is genuinely useless advice. WHEA means hardware. If the Event Viewer points at a specific component and you can’t fix it yourself, send us the WHEA-Logger events and we can tell you exactly what’s failing and whether it’s worth repairing or replacing.\n...\nAlmost always. The most common exception is an unstable overclock — XMP memory profiles, CPU overclocks, or motherboard auto-overclock features pushing components past their stable limit. Reset everything to stock first. If WHEA errors continue at stock settings with no overclocking, it's genuine hardware failure.\n...\nOpen Event Viewer, Windows Logs, System, filter for WHEA-Logger events. The Error Source field tells you: Machine Check Exception means CPU. PCIe Bus Error means GPU, NVMe, or slot issue. If the same CPU core is named in every crash, the CPU die has a defect — contact the manufacturer for warranty replacement.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Repairability Scoring Rubric v1.3 - iFixit\nURL: https://www.ifixit.com/Wiki/Repairability_Scoring_Rubric_v1.3\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nHere you'll find a summary of the various criteria considered when calculating iFixit repairability scores under scorecard version 1.3.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Failing the Fix (2026)\nURL: https://pirg.org/edfund/resources/failing-the-fix-2026/\nPublished: 2026-04-07T00:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nOur fifth edition of “Failing the Fix” reviews the detailed repair information from 105 devices and tracks changes in fixability since our last ...\n\n---\n\nTitle: WHEA Uncorrectable Error Fix | Windows Blue Screen\nURL: https://mdrepairs.com/blog/whea-uncorrectable-error/\nPublished: 2026-04-08T13:00:00.000Z\nAuthor: Joe Montanti\nHighlights:\n, 202\n...\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR is a Windows blue screen (BSOD) that means your computer detected a hardware problem it can’t correct on its own. WHEA stands for Windows Hardware Error Architecture. When this stop code appears, Windows is telling you that something physical failed: your CPU, RAM, hard drive, SSD, or motherboard. This is one of several blue screen errors that can indicate storage problems. The good news is that some causes are fixable with basic troubleshooting. Overheating, outdated drivers, bad BIOS settings. The bad news? If the error keeps coming back, you’re probably looking at a hardware failure. And if your storage drive is the culprit, your data could be at risk.\n...\n## Step-by-Step Fixes for WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\n...\n#### 4 Update Your Drivers\n...\nOutdated chipset, storage controller, and GPU drivers can trigger WHEA errors. Go to your motherboard manufacturer’s website (not Windows Update) and download the latest chipset drivers. Do the same for your GPU from NVIDIA, AMD, or Intel.\n...\n#### 5 Update BIOS/UEFI Firmware\n...\nMotherboard manufacturers\n...\nrelease BIOS updates that fix hardware compatibility issues\n...\nmotherboard manufacturer’s support page\n...\nlatest BIOS version\n...\nt lose power during\n...\n6 Check\n...\nHard Drive or SSD Health\n...\nreported a problem\n...\nCrystalDiskInfo(free\n...\nIt reads the\n...\na health status\n...\n#### 7 Run SFC and DISM\n...\nmonitor for the WHEA error.\n...\n### Update or\n...\nSome WHEA errors caused by dying drives can’t be solved with a driver update or a temperature fix. When the storage hardware itself is failing, the only way to get your data back is professional recovery.\n...\nfree evaluation,\n...\ncan’t recover\n...\nAlmost always, yes. The “hardware” in the name is there for a reason. That said, bad drivers can cause hardware to misbehave, which then triggers the WHEA error. In those cases, updating or rolling back the driver fixes the problem even though it technically manifested as a hardware error. But\n...\nthe time, there’s a genuine hardware issue causing it.\n...\n### Can I fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR without reinstalling Windows?\n...\nIn most cases, yes. Since the error is hardware-related, reinstalling Windows won’t fix the root cause. A fresh Windows install on a failing hard drive will still produce WHEA errors. Focus on the hardware: check temperatures, test RAM, update drivers, and evaluate your storage drive’s health. The only time a reinstall might help is if corrupted system files or driver conflicts are the trigger, and even then, SFC and DISM should handle that without a full reinstall.\n\n---\n\nTitle: How to Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR on Windows 10/11 - Outbyte Official Blog\nURL: https://outbyte.com/blog/how-to-fix-whea_uncorrectable_error-on-windows-10-11/\nPublished: 2025-01-06T06:57:45.000Z\nAuthor: Riley Reed\nHighlights:\nWHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR – An error that normally indicates a hardware problem, which may be in the form of defective hardware or malfunctioning system drivers. The major common causes include:\n...\n- Drivers that are out-of-date or poorly configured\n...\n- Corrupted\n...\n## Solving the WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR on Windows 10/11\n...\nThis error can be due to numerous reasons. Therefore, the solution depends largely on the reason. First probable step could be running some PC repair tool like Outbyte PC Repair that takes care of making your system optimal by removing junk files, repairing corrupt registries among other performance issues.\n...\n### 1. Run CHKDSK\n...\nFirst of all, check your hard drives for errors by using the Windows built-in CHKDSK utility before doing any hardware-related changes. This will, in case something on the disk is wrong, retry the problem with WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR.\n...\n### 2. Reset System Overclocking\n...\nOverclocking the system for higher speeds at times may be the reason behind the overheating and instability in the system, which results in the WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR. Restoring your system to its default settings can resolve the issue.\n...\n- Restart your computer and press the key to enter BIOS setup. It is usually F1, F2, DEL, or ESC.\n- In the BIOS setup utility, head over to your system’s overclocking settings. Commonly, this will be available under Advanced, Performance, or Frequency menus.\n- Reverse the CPU clock settings back to their default values.\n...\n### 3. Update Your PC’s Drivers\n...\nDamaged or outdated drivers will, of course, have a devastating effect on the communication between your hardware and software over time. Keep drivers updated – prevents problems.\n...\n### 4. Troubleshoot RAM Problems\n...\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR can be related to faulty RAM. Run Windows Memory Diagnostic to check for problems.\n...\n- Open Control Panel > System & Security > Administrative Tools, and run Windows Memory Diagnostic.\n- Choose Restart now and check for problems.\n- During the reboot, the tool will scan for any issues with your RAM.\n...\nIf no issues are found, you can rule out RAM problems.\n...\nIt is a stop code to point toward an issue of the hardware and, most probably, is caused by faulty hardware or corrupted system drivers.\n...\nbe caused by outdated drivers?\n...\nYes, any drivers that are outdated or incompatible may cause this error to appear.\n...\n3. How do I fix the error caused by overclocking?\n...\nErrors related to overclocking can be fixed by restoring default settings in your BIOS.\n...\n4. Can a problem with RAM cause a WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR?\n...\nYes, this can be caused by faulty RAM. Open Windows Memory Diagnostic to test your RAM.\n\n---\n\nTitle: Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR Blue Screen Error (0x00000124) in Windows 10/11 - SolutionFall\nURL: https://solutionfall.com/question/fix-whea-uncorrectable-error-blue-screen-error-0x00000124-in-windows-10-11/\nPublished: 2026-02-02T13:19:30.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nFix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR Blue Screen Error (0x00000124) in Windows 10/11 - SolutionFall\n...\n# Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR Blue Screen Error (0x00000124) in Windows 10/11\n...\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR blue screen error (bug check code 0x00000124) occurs when the Windows Hardware Error Architecture detected an uncorrectable hardware error. This BSOD can appear during normal use, gaming, or after a Windows update. Here is a complete guide to diagnose and fix it.\n...\nCPU overheating, failing RAM, unstable overclocking, corrupted BIOS settings, or dying motherboard components.\n...\n## Step-by-Step Fix for WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\n...\n- Reset BIOS to default settings — enter BIOS (usually F2/DEL at boot) and load defaults\n- Remove any overclocking — set CPU and RAM to stock speeds\n- Update BIOS firmware from motherboard manufacturer\n...\n- Keep all drivers updated — use Device Manager or manufacturer tools, not third-party driver updaters\n- Monitor system temperatures using HWMonitor or HWiNFO\n- Run`sfc /scannow` and`DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth` regularly\n- Avoid overclocking unless you have adequate cooling\n- Test RAM periodically with Windows Memory Diagnostic\n...\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR blue screen error (bug check code 0x00000124) occurs when the Windows Hardware Error Architecture detected an uncorrectable hardware error. This BSOD can appear during normal use, gaming, or after a Windows update. Here is a complete guide to diagnose and fix it.\n...\nCPU overheating, failing RAM, unstable overclocking, corrupted BIOS settings, or dying motherboard components.\n...\n## Step-by-Step Fix for WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR\n...\nCheck CPU temperature:\n...\nTest RAM thoroughly:\n...\nCheck WHEA error details:\n...\nEvents 10 |\n...\n- Reset BIOS to default settings — enter BIOS (usually F2/DEL at boot) and load defaults\n- Remove any overclocking — set CPU and RAM to stock speeds\n- Update BIOS firmware from motherboard manufacturer\n...\n## How to Analyze BSOD Dump Files\n...\nWindows saves crash dump files that contain the exact cause of the blue screen:\n...\n- Keep all drivers updated — use Device Manager or manufacturer tools, not third-party driver updaters\n- Monitor system temperatures using HWMonitor or HWiNFO\n- Run`sfc /scannow` and`DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth` regularly\n- Avoid overclocking unless you have adequate cooling\n- Test RAM periodically with Windows Memory Diagnostic\n...\n### How do I fix \"Fix WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR Blue Screen Error (0x00000124) in Windows 10/11\"?\n...\nThe WHEA_UNCORRECTABLE_ERROR blue screen error (bug check code 0x00000124) occurs when the Windows Hardware Error Architecture detected an uncorrectable hardware error. This BSOD can appear during...",
      "status": "success",
